variables","To increase the statistical power of the study","To minimise selection bias","To reduce the required sample size"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EControlling for potential confounding variables\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary purpose of matching in case-control studies. By ensuring cases and controls are similar with respect to important variables like age and smoking status, the researcher can better isolate the relationship between asbestos exposure and lung cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing statistical power\u003C/strong\u003E is not the primary purpose as matching may actually reduce statistical power in some situations by limiting the pool of eligible controls. \u003Cstrong\u003EMinimising selection bias\u003C/strong\u003E is not the main goal, though matching may help reduce some forms of bias. \u003Cstrong\u003EEliminating the need for statistical adjustment\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because even with matching, statistical adjustment may still be necessary for other variables. \u003Cstrong\u003EReducing the required sample size\u003C/strong\u003E is also incorrect as matching often requires larger sample sizes to maintain adequate statistical power.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMatching can be done individually (1:1 matching) where each case is paired with a control of the same age and smoking status, or through frequency matching where the overall distribution of these variables is made similar between groups.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Matching in case-control studies helps control for potential confounding variables by ensuring similar distributions of these variables between cases and controls.","In case control studies individual (1:1) matching pairs each case with one control who shares specific characteristics.","In case control studies frequency matching ensures the overall distribution of matching variables is similar between cases and controls."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004.","Motulsky H. Intuitive Biostatistics: A Nonmathematical Guide to Statistical Thinking. (4th Edition). Oxford University Press Academic US; 2017. Chapter 28; pg. 276."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97238"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17489"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97238"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T10:18:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T10:18:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10179"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115230"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id